{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527185"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:29:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:29:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14190"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14190"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.67,0.06,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6873"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53182"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6873"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14190"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38613"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3051"},{"type":"tags","id":"11090"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15652"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53182"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man is brought to the emergency department with acute alcohol intoxication. He is drowsy, has slurred speech, and demonstrates poor coordination. The treating physician explains to the medical student that alcohol\u0027s effects on the central nervous system are primarily due to its action on specific neurotransmitter systems.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of alcohol on neurotransmitter systems in the brain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits NMDA glutamate receptors","Enhances GABA-A receptor activity","Blocks dopamine reuptake","Antagonises adenosine receptors","Increases endogenous opioid release"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of alcohol on neurotransmitter systems in the brain is enhancing GABA-A receptor activity. Alcohol acts as a positive allosteric modulator of GABA-A receptors, which increases the inhibitory effects of GABA (gamma-aminobutyric acid) in the central nervous system. This enhancement of GABA activity contributes to the sedative, anxiolytic, and motor-impairing effects of alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect or incomplete explanations:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits NMDA glutamate receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: While this is a significant action of alcohol, it is not considered the primary mechanism. However, this inhibition does contribute to alcohol\u0027s depressant effects on the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks dopamine reuptake\u003C/strong\u003E: While alcohol can indirectly affect dopamine levels, this is not its primary mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonises adenosine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: Alcohol can affect adenosine signalling, but this is not its main mechanism of action in producing intoxication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases endogenous opioid release\u003C/strong\u003E: Alcohol can indirectly affect the endogenous opioid system, but this is not its primary mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to enhancing GABA-A receptor activity, alcohol also inhibits glutamate action at NMDA (N-methyl-D-aspartate) receptors. This dual action on GABA (enhancement) and glutamate (inhibition) systems contributes to alcohol\u0027s overall depressant effect on the central nervous system, resulting in symptoms such as drowsiness, slurred speech, and poor coordination observed in acute alcohol intoxication.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alcohol primarily acts as a positive allosteric modulator of GABA-A receptors, enhancing inhibitory neurotransmission.","Alcohol also inhibits glutamate action at NMDA receptors, contributing to its depressant effects on the central nervous system."],"references":["Abrahao KP, Salinas AG, Lovinger DM. Alcohol and the brain: neuronal molecular targets, synapses, and circuits. Neuron. 2017 Dec 20;96(6):1223-38."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38613"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14190"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38613"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-17T08:13:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-17T08:13:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6873"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53182"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta"